        <name>2.3.2.2 Task: Function inversion</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the inverse of the function \(f(x) = {@yy@}\), using the fact that the inverse function must take an input \({@yy@}\) and produce an output \(x\). So \(f^{-1}({@yy@})=x\).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Introduce a new variable \(z\) so that \(z={@yy@}\) and transpose this to find \(x\). Hence write down the inverse function:&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( f^{-1}(x) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the function \(f(x) ={@yy@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We introduce the new variable \(z\) so that \(z={@yy@}\) and transpose this to find \(x.\) So \( x = \frac{{@bb@}-z}{@aa@}.\)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(f^{-1}(z) = \frac{{@bb@}-z}{{@aa@}}\). With&amp;nbsp;\(x\)&amp;nbsp;as its argument the inverse function is&amp;nbsp;\( f^{-1}(x) = {@Ans@} \). Take care the expression is in terms of the stated independent variable.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
